Mrs. Flanders sat on the raised circle of the Roman camp, patching Jacob's breeches;
               only looking up as she sucked the end of her cotton, or when some insect dashed at
               her, boomed in her ear, and was gone.

/* "Then to Silvia let us sing, That Silvia is excelling; She excels each mortal
               thing Upon the dull earth dwelling. To her let us garlands bring," */ sang Elsbeth
               Siddons.

And what is the point of fancy-dress dances? thought Fanny. You meet the same people;
               you wear the same clothes; Mangin gets drunk; Florinda sits on his knee. She flirts
               outrageously—with Nick Bramham just now.

And Betty Flanders even now suspected it, as she read his letter, posted at Milan,
               "Telling me," she complained to Mrs. Jarvis, "really nothing that I want to know";
               but she brooded over it.

They had vanished. There was the Acropolis; but had they reached it? The columns and
               the Temple remain; the emotion of the living breaks fresh on them year after year;
               and of that what remains?

Clara's moors were fine enough. The Phoenicians slept under their piled grey rocks;
               the chimneys of the old mines pointed starkly; early moths blurred the heather-bells;
               cartwheels could be heard grinding on the road far beneath; and the suck and sighing
               of the waves sounded gently, persistently, for ever.
